---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import LeadCapture from '../components/LeadCapture.astro';
const title = 'Late Payment Calculator — Late Fees & Interest | latepaycalc.com';
const description = 'Free late payment calculator. Estimate late fees, interest on overdue invoices, and statutory late-payment penalties under state law. Covers both B2B invoices and employment final-paycheck rules.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Late Payment Calculator</h1>
  <p>Calculate what you're owed on a late invoice or paycheck. This calculator covers both B2B late-fee scenarios (overdue customer invoices, contract late-payment clauses) and US employment final-paycheck penalties. Enter your numbers and get an estimate in seconds — no registration, no paywall.</p>

  <section aria-labelledby="calc-heading">
    <h2 id="calc-heading">Calculate late payment</h2>
    <noscript>
      <p><strong>Note:</strong> the interactive calculator requires JavaScript. Manual formula for invoice late fees: <code>Late fee = Amount overdue &times; (Annual interest rate &divide; 365) &times; Days late</code> if your contract specifies an interest rate.</p>
    </noscript>
    <div id="calculator-island">
      <form class="calc-form" data-pilot-placeholder>
        <label>Amount owed (USD) <input type="number" min="0" step="0.01" placeholder="5000" /></label>
        <label>Days overdue <input type="number" min="0" step="1" placeholder="30" /></label>
        <label>Annual late-payment interest rate (%) <input type="number" min="0" step="0.5" placeholder="8" /></label>
        <label>Late fee (flat, if contract specifies) (USD) <input type="number" min="0" step="0.01" placeholder="50" /></label>
        <label>Type <select><option>B2B invoice / contract</option><option>Employment final paycheck</option></select></label>
        <button type="button">Calculate (interactive version loads with JS)</button>
      </form>
    </div>
  </section>

  <LeadCapture caseType="late_payment" caseTypeLabel="Late Payment / Final Paycheck" />

  <section>
    <h2>How late-payment calculations work</h2>
    <p>Late-payment math depends on what your contract or law says. The two most common scenarios produce very different numbers — and different legal remedies. Here's the core logic behind each:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Flat late fee.</strong> A fixed dollar amount imposed when payment is overdue. Common in service contracts and freelance agreements. Example: "$50 late fee if invoice is more than 30 days past due." Applies once, at the trigger point. No daily accrual.</li>
      <li><strong>Interest on overdue balance.</strong> An annual interest rate applied to the unpaid amount, accruing daily until paid. Formula: <code>Amount &times; (Annual rate &divide; 365) &times; Days late</code>. Example: 8% APR on a $5,000 invoice 30 days late = $5,000 &times; (0.08 &divide; 365) &times; 30 = $32.88. Continues growing until paid, unlike a flat fee.</li>
      <li><strong>Statutory late penalty.</strong> Imposed by state law for specific situations — most commonly, late final paychecks in employment. California's waiting-time penalty under Labor Code § 203 is one full day's wages per day late, capped at 30 days. Massachusetts imposes treble damages. These penalties exist independent of contract terms.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Many commercial contracts combine methods — a flat fee at the trigger point plus accruing interest going forward. The calculator handles both individually and in combination. See our <a href="/methodology">methodology</a> for full formula details and worked examples.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>B2B invoice late fees</h2>
    <p>For overdue customer invoices, your right to a late fee depends primarily on what your contract or invoice terms say. Three possible situations:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Contract specifies a rate.</strong> That rate applies, subject to your state's usury cap for commercial transactions. Most states allow commercial parties to agree to rates well above the statutory default — often up to 18–24% APR in writing.</li>
      <li><strong>Contract is silent on late fees.</strong> You can likely still claim statutory interest at your state's commercial rate in a collection action — typically 4–10% per year. This isn't a "late fee" you can invoice directly, but it adds to what's recoverable when you sue or pursue collections. See your state's commercial code for the specific rate.</li>
      <li><strong>No written contract.</strong> Statutory interest still applies for breach of an oral agreement. Your evidentiary position is weaker, but you're not without recourse.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>One important limit: late fees not disclosed before the work was done are typically unenforceable. A customer who agreed to your standard payment terms — including a late-fee clause — is bound by it. A customer who received a surprise late-fee addition on a past-due invoice they never agreed to may not be.</p>
    <p>For deeper coverage: <a href="/guides/how-late-pay-penalties-are-calculated">How late-pay penalties are calculated</a>.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Employment final paycheck penalties</h2>
    <p>If you're an employee whose final paycheck was paid late — or not at all — state law often provides statutory penalties that go well beyond recovering just the unpaid wages. These penalties are designed to deter employer violations, and in the most employee-favorable states, they can be substantial:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>California (Labor Code § 203).</strong> Waiting-time penalty of one full day's wages per day late, capped at 30 days. For a worker earning $250/day, that's up to $7,500 in penalties — on top of the unpaid wages. The deadline: immediate at termination for involuntary discharge; within 72 hours for voluntary quit without notice.</li>
      <li><strong>Massachusetts.</strong> Treble (triple) damages on the unpaid wages plus mandatory attorney's fees under M.G.L. c. 149, § 150. Final wages due same day as discharge, or next regular payday if employee quit.</li>
      <li><strong>Illinois.</strong> 1% per day penalty on unpaid wages plus attorney's fees under 820 ILCS 115/14. Final wages due next regular payday after termination.</li>
      <li><strong>Texas.</strong> For involuntary termination, final pay due within 6 calendar days. Willful violations: the lesser of treble damages or 4 weeks' wages, plus court costs.</li>
      <li><strong>Other states.</strong> Most require final paychecks on the next regular payday. Penalties vary — statutory damages of 25–100% of unpaid amount are common, plus attorney's fees in many states.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Final-paycheck deadlines also vary by termination type — involuntary discharge typically triggers tighter deadlines than voluntary resignation. See <a href="/guides/final-paycheck-deadlines-by-state">Final paycheck deadlines by state</a> for the full breakdown.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to use a lawyer</h2>
    <p>The calculator helps you understand the numbers. But whether those numbers are actually recoverable in your situation depends on facts a calculator can't see — your contract language, your state's current law, whether the debtor has defenses, whether your statute of limitations has run. As a rough guide:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Under $1,000 in dispute:</strong> Start with small claims court (no attorney required) or your state labor agency for employment claims (free to file).</li>
      <li><strong>$1,000–$10,000:</strong> State labor agency for employment claims. For commercial disputes, evaluate whether small claims covers your amount — many states cap at $5,000–$10,000.</li>
      <li><strong>Over $10,000:</strong> Consult a licensed attorney. For employment wage cases, most attorneys who handle wage claims work on contingency — you pay nothing unless they recover. For commercial disputes, weigh attorney's fees against the likely recovery.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Recent guides</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/guides/how-late-pay-penalties-are-calculated">How late-pay penalties are calculated</a></li>
      <li><a href="/guides/final-paycheck-deadlines-by-state">Final paycheck deadlines by state</a></li>
      <li><a href="/guides/what-to-do-if-paid-late">What to do if you're paid late</a></li>
      <li><a href="/guides/common-late-pay-misconceptions">Common late-pay misconceptions</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <style>
    .calc-form { display:grid;gap:0.75rem;max-width:480px;margin:1rem 0; }
    .calc-form label { display:grid;gap:0.25rem;font-size:0.95rem; }
    .calc-form input, .calc-form select { padding:0.5rem;font-size:1rem;border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:4px; }
    .calc-form button { padding:0.6rem 1rem;background:var(--color-accent);color:white;border:none;border-radius:4px;cursor:pointer;font-size:1rem; }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
